Owing to the fact that the electrospun nanofibers’ and nanowebs’ properties are, largely, affected by electrospinning parameters, many studies were done to clarify the relation between the process parameters and the characteristics of obtained nanofibers and nanowebs. The electrospinning parameters can be classified into three main groups:1,18–21


the polymer solution properties, such as solution concentration, polymer molecular weight, viscosity, surface tension, solution temperature, and conductivity;

process parameters, such as applied voltage, the feeding rate of the polymer solution, the distance between the needle tip and collector, needle properties, polarity, and type of collector;

electrospinning ambient parameters, which include temperature, humidity, pressure, and the air circulation in the electrospinning cabin.
Almost all of these parameters were investigated by researchers for different polymers. For example, one of the first studies in electrospinning processing variables was done by Dietzel et al. in 2001.22 They investigated the effect of processing parameters on the morphology of individual electrospun poly(ethylene oxide) (PEO) nanofibers and electrospun non-woven properties. They found that increasing electrospinning voltage changed the shape of the surface of the polymer solution droplet from which the electrospinning jet originated. In addition, the PEO nanofibers’ diameter will be increased with the increase of solution concentration according to a power law relationship. Macossay et al.23 worked on the effect of needle diameter on the nanofibers’ diameter and the thermal properties of electrospun poly(methyl methacrylate). The scanning electron microscopy (SEM) analysis showed that there was no correlation between the needle diameter and the average nanofiber diameter, but it has been observed that a broader range of nanofiber diameters was obtained with smaller needle diameter.
